  <prompt>
    Create `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/ActionEngine/ActionOrchestrationService.cs` modeled on the existing `AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs` pattern. The service orchestrates an Action run from invocation through Tool dispatch (via `IToolHandlerRegistry` from task 026), gate resolution (via `IGateResolver` from task 030), and audit (via the existing `IAuditLogService`). Define the internal `IActionOrchestrationService` interface so the endpoint layer (task 040) and job handler (task 042) consume the service through a typed seam. G12 acceptance gate: no CRUD-side caller injects `IActionOrchestrationService` directly — verified by grep audit at Step 9.5.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    SPAARKE BFF AI services engineer fluent in the existing `AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs` pattern, the `IToolHandlerRegistry` dispatch surface (task 026), the `IGateResolver` primitive (task 030), and the `IAuditLogService` audit surface. You write services that are testable, idempotent under retry, and respect the ADR-013 facade boundary so CRUD-side consumers never see internal types.
  </role>

  <goal>
    Concrete artifacts:
    1. **`Services/Ai/ActionEngine/IActionOrchestrationService.cs`** — internal interface (not in PublicContracts) with method `Task&lt;ActionRunResult&gt; ExecuteActionAsync(ActionDefinition action, IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, object&gt; parameters, ActionExecutionContext context, CancellationToken ct)`. Marked `internal` (or `public` within `Sprk.Bff.Api` only) — never injected outside `Services/Ai/ActionEngine/`.
    2. **`Services/Ai/ActionEngine/ActionOrchestrationService.cs`** — concrete implementation. Pipeline: (a) load Action Definition + governance block (feature flag check delegated to task 045's policy on the endpoint side); (b) resolve parameters + validate against template parameter schema; (c) for each Tool step: pre-dispatch gate check via `IGateResolver` (if `humanGate.required = true`); (d) Tool dispatch via `IToolHandlerRegistry.DispatchAsync(toolId, parameters, ct)`; (e) post-dispatch audit emission (writes Run record + Tier 2 hash audit + Tier 3 work history per ADR-015 — Tier 3 details extended by task 043's middleware extension); (f) write final `sprk_actionrun` record with ADR-017 canonical status sequence.
    3. **DI registration** — add to `Infrastructure/DI/AddActionEngineModule()` (existing from task 014): `services.AddScoped&lt;IActionOrchestrationService, ActionOrchestrationService&gt;();`. Keep total non-framework DI registrations for the module ≤15 per ADR-010.
    4. **Facade hookup** — wire `IActionEngineFacade` (task 015) implementation to delegate `ExecuteActionAsync` to this orchestrator so CRUD-side callers reach the orchestrator ONLY through the facade. The facade implementation lives in `Services/Ai/PublicContracts/` and is the ONLY type allowed to reference `IActionOrchestrationService` outside `Services/Ai/ActionEngine/`.
    5. **G12 verification artifact** — `notes/spikes/g12-facade-integrity-grep.md` recording the grep `grep -rn "IActionOrchestrationService" src/ --include="*.cs"` showing all references live under `Services/Ai/ActionEngine/` or are the single facade-implementation reference.

    Acceptance: unit test asserts orchestrator runs Tool dispatch → gate check → audit write in order; integration test asserts the orchestrator handles a 2-step Action (e.g., the "Summarize a matter" template — deterministic Dataverse query + AI narrative summary) end-to-end with a Run record persisted.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      The orchestrator is the engine of the Action runtime. It is invoked from THREE callers in MVP:
      1. `ActionEndpoints.cs` `/run` handler (task 040) via the `IActionEngineFacade`.
      2. `ScheduledActionDispatchJobHandler.cs` (task 042) via the same facade.
      3. The `InvokeResource` meta-tool implementation (task 024 — Phase 2) via the same facade.

      All three callers go through `IActionEngineFacade` per ADR-013 refined (2026-05-20). The orchestrator is the single seam where Tool dispatch, gate resolution, and audit converge — there is no other place these three concerns meet.

      Existing pattern reference: `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs` — clone the structural shape (constructor injection of dependencies, scoped service lifetime, cancellation token propagation, structured logging with correlation id). The Action orchestrator differs in two ways: (a) it walks a Tool step list rather than running a single analysis pipeline; (b) it interleaves gate checks between Tool dispatches when `humanGate.required = true`.

      ADR-015 audit choke point: `IToolHandlerRegistry` (task 026) is documented as "the audit choke point" for Tool dispatch. The orchestrator does NOT write audit directly — it lets the registry write the per-dispatch audit, then writes the per-Run audit on completion. Task 043 extends `AuditEnrichmentMiddleware` to add Tool-dispatch enrichment fields; this orchestrator emits the events that the middleware enriches.

      Run record status sequence (ADR-017 canonical): `Queued → Running → Completed | Failed | Poisoned | Cancelled`. The orchestrator owns transitions; `ScheduledActionDispatchJobHandler` (task 042) sets `Queued`, the orchestrator sets `Running` on entry and the terminal state on exit.

      G12 acceptance gate: `IActionOrchestrationService` is `internal`-scoped to the Action Engine. CRUD-side callers must NEVER inject it directly — they go through `IActionEngineFacade` (task 015). This task establishes the boundary; the grep audit at Step 9.5 enforces it.

      Binding governance: `.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md` MUST be loaded. Placement = BFF per spec.md §6. ≤5MB publish-size delta tracked at the module level. No new NuGet packages.
    </background>
