  <notes>
    `AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs` is the structural reference. Read it carefully — the Action orchestrator is the "Action world" version of the same shape. Differences: (a) Tool step list with interleaved gate checks; (b) Run record persistence is owned by this service, not the facade.

    The orchestrator does NOT write per-Tool-dispatch audit directly — that's `IToolHandlerRegistry` (task 026, the audit choke point per ADR-015). The orchestrator emits one Run-completion audit event. Task 043 extends the middleware to enrich Tool-dispatch events with Action-Engine-specific fields (`actionId`, `runId`, `phase`).

    The internal-scope of `IActionOrchestrationService` is the load-bearing piece for G12. If you find a CRUD-side caller wanting to inject the orchestrator directly, route them through `IActionEngineFacade` (task 015). The facade is the ONLY allowable seam.

    Do NOT add a new orchestrator-internal audit service. `IAuditLogService` (existing) is sufficient. Task 043's extension is to the existing `AuditEnrichmentMiddleware`, not a new service.

    Spec.md §NFR-08 (idempotency / retry) applies primarily to task 042 (job handler). The orchestrator itself can assume the caller has handled idempotency (job handler uses `IIdempotencyService`; endpoint uses request-ids if applicable). The orchestrator stays straightforward.

    The 3 MVP starter templates (FR-19/FR-20/FR-21) all flow through this orchestrator. Phase 5 tasks (052-055) build templates AGAINST this orchestrator — do not block on them. Get the orchestrator right and they slot in.
  </notes>

